# Domain layer

`src/domain/` holds **shared business logic** — not UI. Multiple surfaces may import it: public web, Hyperview, creator dashboard, admin, API, cron, auth.

## Put code in domain when

- API, cron, `(app)/`, `hyperview/`, claims, or auth needs it
- It mutates/queries core entities (books, creators, notifications, planner state)
- It's a service or pure function with no JSX
- A second non-admin caller appears — extract on import pressure, don't pre-split everything

## Keep code in features when

- It's a component, Alpine client, admin table, modal, or HTML partial
- Only admin moderation/planner screens use it
- Moving it would drag admin UI along (e.g. Brevo send panels, Instagram prep modals)

## Import boundaries

```typescript
// ✅ public / hyperview route
import { createBookLikedNotification } from "../../domain/notifications/utils";

// ❌ public / hyperview route — blocked by npm run lint
import { createBookLikedNotification } from "../../features/dashboard/admin/notifications/utils";
```

- `domain/` must not import `features/dashboard/admin/**` UI
- When extracting from admin, leave a re-export in the old path if it reduces churn
- Split mixed files: move shared runners/queries to domain; keep admin workflow glue in admin

## Client bundles

- `src/client/index.ts` → `main.js` (public + creator Alpine)
- `src/client/admin.ts` → `admin.js` (admin-only; loaded on `/dashboard/admin/*`)

Register new Alpine components in the bundle that matches who uses them.
